# Release workflow

Releases are **tag-driven**. Pushing a `v<version>` tag to `origin`
fires `.github/workflows/release.yml`, which builds every publishable
workspace and runs `dbxtools release` against npm.

There is no PR-based versioning bot and no auto-publish on push to
`main`. The tag push is the deliberate ship signal.

## Cutting a release

```bash
bun run tag                 # patch bump (default)
bun run tag minor           # minor bump
bun run tag major           # major bump
bun run tag --dry-run       # preview without writing or pushing
```

`dbxtools tag` (the `tag()` function in `@dbx-tools/cli`) handles the
full sequence in one shot:

1. Reads the shared version from the first publishable package and
   sanity-checks every other publishable package matches it
   (changesets `fixed` policy).
2. Bumps the version with `semver.inc()` and writes it back to every
   publishable `package.json`.
3. Auto-stages dirty files (`git add -A`) and folds them into the
   release commit `chore: release v<version>`.
4. Pushes the commit, creates an annotated `v<version>` tag, pushes
   the tag.
5. Creates the GitHub Release (when `gh` is on `PATH`) and runs the
   local publish path (`bun run release`) unless `--no-publish`.

The annotated tag and GitHub Release both use a plain
`Release v<version>` message.

## Local publish (debugging / one-off)

```bash
dbxtools build
dbxtools release --dry-run            # bun publish --dry-run per package
bun run release                     # build + real publish
```

`dbxtools release` first runs `dbxtools build`, then for each publishable
package it temporarily _stamps_ a complete `package.json` (expands the
slim `exports` source pointer into the `source`/`types`/`default`
shape and fills in `main`, `types`, `files`, `license`, `type`), runs
`bun publish` from the package dir, and restores the original slim
manifest afterward - on success or failure. The committed
`package.json` files stay slim; only the published tarballs are
complete.

## Don't auto-deploy

Per workspace rules, never run `bun run tag`, `bun run release`,
`databricks bundle deploy`, or `git push` without the user explicitly
asking in the current message. "Tag it", "ship it", "release it",
"deploy" all count as explicit consent.
